{{Paleolithic|upper}}
'''Ahmarian''' culture<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsweek.com/ancient-european-culture-spectacular-cave-painting-middle-east-762051|title=Archaeologists carbon dated a cave in Israel to reveal details about the two first modern human cultures|date=28 December 2017|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.jhevol.2015.02.017 |pmid=25924809 |title=Variability in Early Ahmarian lithic technology and its implications for the model of a Levantine origin of the Protoaurignacian |journal=Journal of Human Evolution |volume=82 |pages=67–87 |year=2015 |last1=Kadowaki |first1=Seiji |last2=Omori |first2=Takayuki |last3=Nishiaki |first3=Yoshihiro }}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|doi=10.1007/978-981-10-6826-3_7 |chapter=The Ahmarian in the Context of the Earlier Upper Palaeolithic in the Near East |title=The Middle and Upper Paleolithic Archeology of the Levant and Beyond |pages=87–104 |year=2018 |last1=Goring-Morris |first1=Nigel |last2=Belfer-Cohen |first2=Anna |isbn=978-981-10-6825-6 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1007/BF00974677 |title=The Upper Paleolithic period in the Levant |journal=Journal of World Prehistory |volume=5 |issue=2 |pages=105–154 |year=1991 |last1=Gilead |first1=Isaac }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.pl/books?id=rla-BAAAQBAJ&pg=PA61&lpg=PA61&dq=ahmarian+levant+emiran+aurignacian&source=bl&ots=V6uPOVdcmZ&sig=tFz7nQyfVuHJX9f_3ouXMcuxXNM&hl=pl&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiH4Kia6IvZAhWQu1MKHaBOBNMQ6AEIRDAI#v=onepage&q=ahmarian+levant+emiran+aurignacian&f=false|title=Dynamics of Learning in Neanderthals and Modern Humans Volume 1: Cultural Perspectives|first1=Takeru|last1=Akazawa|first2=Yoshihiro|last2=Nishiaki|first3=Kenichi|last3=Aoki|date=16 December 2013|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>https://books.google.pl/books?id=KzZCDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA129&lpg=PA129&dq=caucasus+imereti+industry&source=bl&ots=--EAGrtFCs&sig=7M9-bWmwtk5GmJ97pW5Z5t0T3D0&hl=pl&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiM4pqNoYzZAhXN2VMKHc8hDkUQ6AEIbzAN#v=onepage&q=caucasus%20imereti%20industry&f=false</ref> was a [[Paleolithic]] [[archeological industry]] in [[Levant]] dated at 46,000-42,000 BP and  thought to be related to Levantine [[Emiran]] and younger European [[Aurignacian]] cultures. Ahmarian is considered to be the likely source of first modern humans who migrated to Europe to form Aurignacian culture known as [[European early modern humans|Cro-Magnon]]s. Although European [[Bohunician]] culture that may be linked to Emiran and Ahmarian itself and dated at 48,000 BP may predate it.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1073/pnas.0903446106 |title=The spread of modern humans in Europe |journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences |volume=106 |issue=38 |pages=16040–16045 |year=2009 |last1=Hoffecker |first1=J. F |pmc=2752585 }}</ref> There is also a claim that it is roughly contemporary with the Aurignacian and the [[Gravettian]] cultures of Europe, all emerging prior to the Athlitian, which was also contemporary with the [[Solutrean]] and [[Magdalenian]] cultures of Western Europe.<ref>{{Cite book|title=A History of Israel and the Holy Land|last=Avi-Yonah|first=Michael|publisher=Continuum|year=2001|isbn=0826413226|location=New York|pages=20}}</ref>

The technical knowledge of the Ahmarian culture, along with the other lithic industries, is considered the likely source of the abrupt and rapid takeover of the world in all directions as evidenced by the crossing of the [[Bering Strait]] towards America.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Gobekli Tepe: An Introduction to the World's Oldest Temple (Revised Edition)|last=Bachenheimer|first=Avi|publisher=Blurb, Incorporated|year=2016|isbn=9781366700940|location=San Francisco, CA|pages=19-20}}</ref> Ahmarian technology, which included the complex of blade/bladelet-knapping techniques is also linked to the tools used by the [[Hunter-gatherer|hunter-gatherers]] of south-western Asia.<ref>{{Cite book|title=History of Humanity: Prehistory and the beginnings of civilization|last=De Laet|first=S.J.|last2=Dani|first2=A.H.|last3=Lorenzo|first3=J.L.|last4=Nunoo|first4=R.B.|publisher=Routledge|year=1994|isbn=0415093058|location=London|pages=244}}</ref> 

