{{italic title}}
The '''''Annales Ceccanenses''''', also called the '''''Chronicon Fossae novae''''', is a chronicle of [[world history]] from the [[birth of Jesus]] down to 1218. It was a written in the late twelfth and early thirteenth century by an anonymous monk of [[Fossanova Abbey]], near [[Ceccano]]. It is partially dependent on the ''[[Annales Cavenses]]'' and ''[[Annales Casinenses]]'', and contains no original material prior to the year 1120. After that it is a valuable source for the history of the [[Papacy]].<ref>[[Auguste Molinier]], [https://www-persee-fr.bibliopam-evry.univ-evry.fr/web/ouvrages/home/prescript/article/shf_0000-0000_1903_num_3_1_919_t1_0021_0000_6# "2289. Annales Ceccanenses"]{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} ''Les Sources de l'histoire de France—Des origines aux guerres d'Italie. III. Les Capétiens, 1180–1328'' (Paris: A. Picard et fils, 1903), p. 21.</ref>

